To evaluate \(\cos\frac{\pi}{4}\), consider an isosceles right triangle with legs of length 1.  Then the hypotenuse is \(\sqrt{1^2+1^2}=\sqrt2\).  At the 45° (π/4) angle, the adjacent side is 1 and the hypotenuse is \(\sqrt2\), so

\[
\cos\frac{\pi}{4}=\frac{\text{adjacent}}{\text{hypotenuse}}
=\frac{1}{\sqrt2}
=\frac{\sqrt2}{2}.
\]
